<h1>Chapter 7</h1>

<h2>7.1 Introduction</h2>

<p>
Graphical presentation of data is an effective way of representing statistical information. 
Graphs help to understand relationships between variables easily and clearly. 
Compared with tables, graphs provide a more attractive and visual representation of data.
</p>

<p>
A graph shows the relationship between two or more sets of data using points and lines. 
It allows comparisons and helps even non-experts understand statistical information.
</p>

---

<h2>7.2 Difference Between Graph and Diagram</h2>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Sl No</th>
<th>Diagram</th>
<th>Graph</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>1</td>
<td>Represented using pictures such as bars, squares, circles etc.</td>
<td>Represented using points and lines.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>2</td>
<td>Can be drawn on any paper.</td>
<td>Requires graph paper.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>3</td>
<td>Cannot locate measures like median or mode.</td>
<td>Can help locate median and mode.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>4</td>
<td>Used for categorical or geographical data.</td>
<td>Used for time series and frequency distribution.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>5</td>
<td>Shows approximate idea.</td>
<td>Shows exact information.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>6</td>
<td>More impressive visually.</td>
<td>Less impressive visually.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>7</td>
<td>Creates lasting impression.</td>
<td>Less lasting effect.</td>
</tr>

</table>

---

<h2>7.3 Advantages of Graphical Representation</h2>

<ul>

<li>Facilitates comparison between variables.</li>

<li>Shows relationship or correlation between variables.</li>

<li>Helps analyze effects of various factors.</li>

<li>Useful for forecasting future trends.</li>

<li>Assists in statistical analysis and research planning.</li>

<li>More useful than diagrams for time-series and frequency data.</li>

</ul>

---

<h2>7.4 Limitations</h2>

<ul>

<li>Graphs cannot show all details available in tables.</li>

<li>Graphs give approximate values only.</li>

<li>Drawing graphs requires more time.</li>

<li>Graphs may not show accuracy of data.</li>

</ul>

---

<h2>Types of Graphical Representation</h2>

<p>Graphs are mainly used for two statistical series:</p>

<ul>

<li>Time Series Data</li>

<li>Frequency Distribution</li>

</ul>

---

<h2>7.5 Time Series Graph (Historigram)</h2>

<p>
Time-series graphs show data over time. 
Time is plotted on the X-axis and the variable value on the Y-axis.
</p>

<h3>1. One Variable Historigram</h3>

<p>
Only one variable is plotted against time.
Points are joined by straight lines to show trends.
</p>

<h3>2. Historigram for Two or More Variables</h3>

<p>
Two or more variables measured in the same units can be plotted on the same graph.
Different line styles are used for each variable.
</p>

<h3>3. Historigram with Two Scales</h3>

<p>
When variables have different units, two vertical scales are used
(left Y-axis and right Y-axis).
</p>

<h3>4. Belt Graph (Band Curve)</h3>

<p>
A belt graph shows total values divided into components for each time period.
The regions between lines are shaded with colors.
</p>

<h3>5. Range Graph</h3>

<p>
A range graph shows maximum and minimum values for each period.
Example: daily maximum and minimum temperature.
</p>

---

<h2>7.6 Frequency Distribution Graphs</h2>

<p>
Frequency distributions can be represented using several types of graphs:
</p>

<ul>

<li>Histogram</li>

<li>Frequency Polygon</li>

<li>Frequency Curve</li>

<li>Ogives (Cumulative Frequency Curve)</li>

</ul>

---

<h2>1. Histogram</h2>

<p>
Histogram is the most widely used graph for frequency distributions.
It consists of adjacent rectangles where:
</p>

<ul>

<li>Width = Class Interval</li>

<li>Height = Frequency</li>

</ul>

<p>
Class intervals are shown on the X-axis and frequencies on the Y-axis.
</p>

<h3>Construction Steps</h3>

<ol>

<li>Convert inclusive classes to exclusive if necessary.</li>

<li>Plot class intervals on X-axis.</li>

<li>Plot frequencies on Y-axis.</li>

<li>Draw rectangles with heights equal to frequencies.</li>

<li>Rectangles must touch each other.</li>

</ol>

---

<h3>Histogram for Unequal Class Intervals</h3>

<p>
When class intervals are unequal, frequency density is used instead of frequency.
</p>

<p><b>Frequency Density = Frequency / Class Width</b></p>

---

<h3>Difference Between Histogram and Bar Diagram</h3>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Histogram</th>
<th>Bar Diagram</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Two-dimensional diagram</td>
<td>One-dimensional diagram</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Bars touch each other</td>
<td>Bars separated by gaps</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Used for frequency distributions</td>
<td>Used for categorical data</td>
</tr>

</table>

---

<h2>2. Frequency Polygon</h2>

<p>
A frequency polygon is obtained by joining the midpoints of the tops of histogram rectangles.
</p>

<p>
Alternatively, points representing class midpoints and frequencies are joined by straight lines.
</p>

---

<h2>3. Frequency Curve</h2>

<p>
A frequency curve is similar to a frequency polygon but uses a smooth curve instead of straight lines.
</p>

---

<h2>4. Ogives (Cumulative Frequency Curve)</h2>

<p>
An ogive is a graph of cumulative frequencies.
It is used to determine values like median, quartiles, deciles, and percentiles.
</p>

<h3>Types of Ogives</h3>

<ul>

<li><b>Less Than Ogive</b> – cumulative frequencies plotted using upper class limits.</li>

<li><b>More Than Ogive</b> – cumulative frequencies plotted using lower class limits.</li>

</ul>

<p>
The intersection of these two curves gives the median graphically.
</p>

---

<h2>Advantages of Ogive Curve</h2>

<ul>

<li>Helps compute median, quartiles, and percentiles graphically.</li>

<li>Shows number of observations below or above certain values.</li>

<li>Useful for comparing distributions.</li>

</ul>

